<ab><lb n="1"/>  <w lemma="ὁ">ἡ</w>  <w lemma="σορός">σορός</w>  <w lemma="εἰμί">ἐστιν</w>  <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μᾶρκος">Μάρκ<unclear reason="damage">ου</unclear></name>  <name nymRef="#Αὐρήλιος"><unclear reason="damage">Αὐ</unclear>ρηλι<lb n="3" break="no"/>ου</name>  <name nymRef="#Ἀντίοχος">Ἀντιόχου</name> <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w> <lb n="4"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Εἰσαγόρας"><orig n="unresolved"><unclear reason="damage">εισα</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="8" unit="character"/>  </name></persName></persName><lb n="5"/><orig n="unresolved">ω</orig>  <gap reason="lost" extent="1" unit="character"/>  <orig n="unresolved"><unclear reason="damage">λ</unclear></orig>  <gap reason="lost" extent="9" unit="character"/>  <lb n="5a"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>The sarcophagus belongs to Marcus Aurelius Antiochus the son of Eis[- ... <note>(perhaps Eisagoras)</note>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Probably one of the shorter type texts; but the owner, although apparently possessing only the sarcophagus, gave his Roman name in full and cited at least his father's name in the Greek manner, suggesting a date not too long after the Edict of Caracalla in A.D. 212.</p>
         </div>
